2500|$|It {{is thought}} that Whetstone was named after the {{whetstone}} used to sharpen knives and other tools, a chunk of which {{is located on the}} High Road, on the pavement outside the Griffin pub (see picture). [...] Some [...] question this and suggest the stone was placed there as a mounting block for climbing on to horses as the Griffin was a coaching inn. It is also said that the name <b>Whestone</b> is merely a corruption of an old Anglo-Saxon name. Legend has it that it was used by soldiers about to fight in the Battle of Barnet.|$|E
50|$|The {{village was}} {{formerly}} known as <b>Whestone.</b>|$|E
